{"name": ".AM-2: Triage + Draft", "version": "2.8.0", "description": "Morning ritual: curate the day with per-task context + next actions + pre-drafted comms, interactive Asana command center, ABPS AI Project intake scan + date window checks + near-due escalation + overdue flagging + refresh cadence checks, portfolio project scan (AU, MX, WW Testing, WW Acq, Paid App) with enrichment + date checks + status staleness + recurring tasks + blocker detection + event countdown + budget tracking + context refresh, Kiro_RW writes, email drafts. Feeds AM-3.", "when": {"type": "userTriggered"}, "then": {"type": "askAgent", "prompt": "Run AM-2: Triage + Draft.\n\nCONTEXT: spine.md, current.md, memory.md, richard-writing-style.md, hands.md, amcc.md, rw-tracker.md, asana-command-center.md, ALL intake/ files.\n\nPHASE 1 \u2014 PROCESS INTAKE:\n- Slack [ACTION-RW] signals \u2192 create Asana tasks if actionable (assign to Richard, set Routine + Priority_RW based on signal type). SIGNAL-TO-ROUTINE MAPPING: Quick reply/send/confirm \u2192 Sweep + Today. Strategic discussion/artifact/framework \u2192 Core + Urgent. Campaign/keyword/bid/spreadsheet work \u2192 Engine Room + Today. Admin/budget/invoice/compliance \u2192 Admin + Today. Unclear/ambiguous \u2192 no Routine (Backlog) + flag for triage.\n- Email signals \u2192 same routing to Asana using the signal-to-Routine mapping above.\n- Asana digest \u2192 update hands.md Priority Actions from Asana state (Asana is source of truth, hands.md is the snapshot).\n- SLACK DECISION DETECTION: When processing Slack threads from intake/, detect decision signals \u2014 keywords: 'decided', 'agreed', 'confirmed', 'approved', 'going with', 'final call', 'locked in'. For each detected decision: extract the decision text, thread link, participants, and date. Queue for Project Notes 'Recent Decisions & Changes' section update on the relevant project (match by task/project context). Format: 'YYYY-MM-DD: [Decision summary] (Source: Slack thread [link]). Participants: [names].' Present queued decisions to Richard during Phase 2 for approval before writing to Asana Project Notes.\n- Check Routine bucket caps: Sweep 5, Core 4, Engine Room 6, Admin 3. If over cap, flag lowest-priority for demotion.\n- Tasks with Priority_RW=Today but no Routine \u2192 flag for Richard to assign a block.\n- Overdue 7+ days with no activity \u2192 flag for decision: do, delegate, or kill.\n\nPHASE 1 ENHANCEMENT \u2014 MY TASKS DEEP ENRICHMENT:\nAfter processing intake signals above, scan ALL incomplete My Tasks for field completeness gaps. Call SearchTasksInWorkspace(assignee_any='1212732742544167', completed='false') to get all incomplete tasks. For each task, call GetTaskDetails(task_gid, opt_fields='name,assignee.gid,due_on,start_on,completed,custom_fields.name,custom_fields.display_value,custom_fields.gid,memberships.section.name') to read fields.\n\nFor each incomplete task, check these four enrichment rules:\n\n1. KIRO_RW CHECK (GID: 1213915851848087):\n   IF Kiro_RW is empty/null OR does not match M/D brevity format (pattern: digit(s)/digit(s): <text under 10 words>):\n   \u2192 Propose a Kiro_RW entry using today's date in M/D format (no leading zeros). Derive status from task name, due date, and Routine.\n   Example: '4/15: Active. Due Friday. No blockers.'\n   Queue for enrichment batch.\n\n2. NEXT ACTION CHECK (GID: 1213921400039514):\n   IF Next action is empty/null:\n   \u2192 Propose a Next action based on task name, subtasks, and context.\n   Format: imperative verb, single sentence, <15 words.\n   Example: 'Send AU invoice to finance by EOD Friday'\n   Queue for enrichment batch.\n\n3. DATE CHECK (Begin Date GID: 1213440376528542):\n   IF due_on is set but start_on (Begin Date) is null:\n   \u2192 Propose start_on = max(today, due_on - 7 calendar days).\n   ASANA CONSTRAINT: start_on requires due_on. Only propose when due_on exists.\n   Queue for enrichment batch.\n\n4. PRIORITY_RW DEFAULT (GID: 1212905889837829):\n   IF Routine (GID: 1213608836755502) is set (any value) but Priority_RW is null/empty:\n   \u2192 Propose Priority_RW = 'Not urgent' (option GID: 1212905889837833).\n   Queue for enrichment batch.\n\nAfter scanning all tasks, present proposed enrichments to Richard:\n\n\ud83d\udcdd MY TASKS ENRICHMENT \u2014 [N] task(s) need field updates:\n\nFor each task with gaps:\n- [task name] (GID: [gid])\n  - Kiro_RW: [proposed entry] (currently: [empty or current value])\n  - Next action: [proposed entry] (currently: empty)\n  - Begin Date: [proposed YYYY-MM-DD] (currently: unset)\n  - Priority_RW: Not urgent (currently: empty)\n- ACTION: Approve all, approve individually, or skip?\n\nOnly show fields that need enrichment for each task \u2014 omit fields that are already populated correctly.\n\nEXECUTE APPROVED ENRICHMENTS:\nFor each approved task, build the UpdateTask call with all approved fields in a single operation:\n- Kiro_RW + Next action via custom_fields: UpdateTask(task_gid, custom_fields={'1213915851848087': '[kiro_rw]', '1213921400039514': '[next_action]'})\n- Begin Date via start_on: include start_on='YYYY-MM-DD' in the same UpdateTask call (only if due_on is already set).\n- Priority_RW via custom_fields: add '1212905889837829': '1212905889837833' to the custom_fields object.\n- Combine all field writes into one UpdateTask call per task to minimize API calls.\n- AUDIT: Log each write to ~/shared/context/active/asana-audit-log.jsonl with project='My_Tasks'.\n  Format: {timestamp, tool:'UpdateTask', task_gid, task_name, project:'My_Tasks', fields_modified:[list], result:'success'|'failure', notes:'Phase 1 Enhancement enrichment'}\n- API FAILURE: On failure \u2192 log \u2192 retry once after 2s \u2192 if retry fails, skip task and flag in daily brief.\n\nNote: This enhancement runs BEFORE Phase 1B (ABPS AI Content scan). Near-due escalation and overdue flagging for My Tasks are handled separately \u2014 this phase only covers field completeness enrichment proposals.\n\nPHASE 1B \u2014 ABPS AI PROJECT SCAN:\nScan the ABPS AI - Content project alongside My Tasks. This is the autonomous document factory \u2014 Richard drops ideas into Intake, the agent triages them.\n\nGUARDRAIL PROTOCOL (applies to ALL ABPS AI writes in this phase):\nAll write operations in Phase 1B MUST follow the Guardrail Protocol defined in asana-command-center.md \u00a7 Guardrail Protocol. Quick reference:\n- PRE-WRITE: GetTaskDetails first, verify assignee.gid === '1212732742544167' (Richard). Block if not Richard's task.\n- AUDIT LOG: Append JSON line to ~/shared/context/active/asana-audit-log.jsonl for every write. Use extended format: {timestamp, tool, task_gid, task_name, project:'ABPS_AI_Project', pipeline_agent, pipeline_stage, fields_modified, result, notes}.\n- READ-BEFORE-WRITE: Before any UpdateTask(html_notes): read current content, check for Richard's additions since last agent write (compare Kiro_RW timestamps), preserve Richard's content.\n- API FAILURE: On failure \u2192 log to audit log + Kiro_RW \u2192 retry once \u2192 if retry fails, flag for manual attention in daily brief. Max one retry per failure.\nSee asana-command-center.md for full protocol details.\n\nSTEP 1 \u2014 SCAN INTAKE FOR UNTRIAGED TASKS:\n- Call GetTasksFromProject(project_gid='1213917352480610') to get all incomplete tasks from ABPS AI - Content.\n- For each task returned, call GetTaskDetails(task_gid, opt_fields='name,assignee.name,due_on,completed,notes,custom_fields.name,custom_fields.display_value,memberships.section.name') to read custom fields, dates, and section membership.\n- FILTER for untriaged tasks: tasks in the Intake section (GID: 1213917352480612) where the Routine field (GID: 1213608836755502) is NOT set (null/empty). These are tasks Richard dropped in but the agent hasn't triaged yet.\n- Skip tasks that already have a Routine value \u2014 those have been triaged and are waiting for their date window.\n\nSTEP 2 \u2014 ANALYZE EACH UNTRIAGED TASK:\nFor each untriaged Intake task, prepare triage recommendations:\n- Read the task name and description to understand what Richard wants.\n- Determine recommended field values:\n  - Routine bucket (Sweep/Core/Engine Room/Admin) based on content type\n  - Priority_RW (Today/Urgent/Not urgent) based on urgency signals\n  - Frequency (weekly/monthly/quarterly/one-time via field GID 1213921303350613) based on whether the deliverable is recurring or one-time\n  - Work_Product type: guide, reference, decision, playbook, or analysis\n- Check for Begin Date (start_on) and Due Date (due_on):\n  - If start_on is null AND due_on is null: recommend Begin Date = today, Due Date = today + 7 calendar days\n  - If start_on is null AND due_on is set: recommend Begin Date = today (keep existing Due Date)\n  - If start_on is set AND due_on is null: recommend Due Date = today + 7 calendar days (keep existing Begin Date)\n  - If both dates are already set: keep original values \u2014 do NOT overwrite\n  - ASANA CONSTRAINT: start_on requires due_on to be set. Always ensure due_on is set when setting start_on.\n  - Format: YYYY-MM-DD (e.g., 2026-04-15)\n  - Show which dates are defaults vs. original in the triage presentation so Richard can see what will be set\n- Draft a one-sentence scope statement describing what the Work_Product will cover.\n\nSTEP 3 \u2014 PRESENT TRIAGE DECISIONS TO RICHARD:\nDo NOT auto-execute any changes. Present all findings for Richard's approval:\n\n\ud83d\udce5 ABPS AI Intake \u2014 [N] untriaged task(s) found:\n\nFor each task:\n- TASK: [name] (GID: [gid])\n- DESCRIPTION: [first 100 chars or summary]\n- RECOMMENDED TRIAGE:\n  - Routine: [bucket]\n  - Priority_RW: [level]\n  - Frequency: [cadence]\n  - Work_Product: [type]\n  - Begin Date: [YYYY-MM-DD] [if default: '\u2190 default (today)']\n  - Due Date: [YYYY-MM-DD] [if default: '\u2190 default (today+7)']\n  - Scope: [one-sentence scope statement]\n- ACTION NEEDED: Approve triage, adjust fields, or skip?\n\nNote: Date defaults are applied AFTER Richard approves \u2014 they are part of the field write, not pre-applied. Richard can override any default date before approval.\n\nSTEP 3B \u2014 EXECUTE APPROVED TRIAGE (after Richard approves each task):\nFor each approved task, execute the field writes:\n- Set Routine, Priority_RW, Frequency, and Kiro_RW via UpdateTask(custom_fields={...})\n- APPLY DATE DEFAULTS (only for tasks missing dates):\n  - If start_on was null: UpdateTask(task_gid, start_on='YYYY-MM-DD') where date = today\n  - If due_on was null: UpdateTask(task_gid, due_on='YYYY-MM-DD') where date = today + 7 calendar days\n  - IMPORTANT: start_on requires due_on (Asana constraint). If setting start_on, always set due_on in the same call or ensure it's already set.\n  - Combined call: UpdateTask(task_gid, start_on='2026-04-15', due_on='2026-04-22', custom_fields={...})\n  - Do NOT overwrite dates that were already set on the task\n- Append date default notation to Kiro_RW entry if defaults were applied: add '(defaults: begin=today, due=today+7)' or whichever defaults were used\n\nSTEP 3C \u2014 SECTION MOVE + RESEARCH SUBTASK (after field writes complete):\nAfter all custom fields and dates are written, determine section placement based on Begin Date:\n\nIF Begin Date (start_on) <= today:\n  1. MOVE TASK TO IN PROGRESS SECTION:\n     - Use UpdateTask to set the task's project section to In Progress.\n     - Call: UpdateTask(task_gid=[task_gid], assignee_section='1213917923741223')\n     - NOTE: assignee_section moves tasks within My Tasks sections. For project section moves, the Asana API uses the addTask endpoint on a section. Since the Enterprise Asana MCP may not expose a direct AddTaskToSection tool, try UpdateTask first. If that doesn't move the task within the project, use the following fallback: check if the task appears in the In Progress section after the UpdateTask call by reading GetTaskDetails and inspecting memberships.section. If still in Intake, the section move needs manual verification.\n     - VERIFICATION: After the move call, confirm the task's section by checking GetTaskDetails \u2192 memberships \u2192 section.gid. It should be '1213917923741223' (In Progress), not '1213917352480612' (Intake).\n  2. CREATE RESEARCH SUBTASK:\n     - This is the first pipeline subtask \u2014 it signals the task has entered the pipeline.\n     - Call: CreateTask(name='\ud83d\udccb Research: [parent task name]', parent=[task_gid], assignee='1212732742544167', project='1213917352480610')\n     - The subtask name MUST follow the exact pattern: '\ud83d\udccb Research: [parent task name]' where [parent task name] is the exact name of the parent task.\n     - Assigned to Richard (GID: 1212732742544167).\n     - Added to the ABPS AI Content project (GID: 1213917352480610) so it appears in the project view.\n  3. UPDATE KIRO_RW: Append to the existing Kiro_RW entry: ' \u2192 Moved to In Progress, research subtask created.'\n\nIF Begin Date (start_on) > today:\n  - Leave the task in Intake with all fields applied. The task waits for its date window.\n  - The AM-2 date window check (Phase 1B, Step 3H) will pick it up when Begin Date arrives.\n  - UPDATE KIRO_RW: Append to the existing Kiro_RW entry: ' \u2192 Stays in Intake (begin date future: [start_on]).'\n  - No subtask creation \u2014 the pipeline doesn't start until the task enters its date window.\n\nWait for Richard's direction on each task before writing any fields or moving sections. This is the human-in-the-loop gate for triage.\n\nSTEP 3D \u2014 PIPELINE INITIATION (research stage):\nAfter triage section moves are complete, check for tasks that need pipeline initiation. This is how the ABPS AI document factory starts producing work.\n\nFor ALL tasks in the In Progress section (GID: 1213917923741223) \u2014 not just newly triaged ones:\n1. Call GetSubtasksForTask(task_gid) to check for pipeline subtasks.\n2. Look for a subtask matching the pattern '\ud83d\udccb Research: [name]' that is NOT completed (completed === false).\n3. IF an incomplete research subtask exists AND the task's Begin Date (start_on) <= today:\n   - This task has entered its date window and needs Stage 1 (Research) executed.\n   - INVOKE wiki-researcher agent with the following context:\n     a. Task GID and task name\n     b. Task description (Richard's original idea)\n     c. Kiro_RW field content (triage context, scope statement)\n     d. Work_Product type (from Kiro_RW triage entry)\n   - The wiki-researcher will:\n     a. Gather source material from: body system organs, DuckDB (ps-analytics), Slack channels, Outlook email, web search\n     b. Post a research brief as a PINNED comment: CreateTaskStory(task_gid, html_text='<body>..research brief..</body>', is_pinned='true')\n     c. Complete the '\ud83d\udccb Research: [name]' subtask: UpdateTask(subtask_gid, completed='true')\n     d. Log stage transition: CreateTaskStory(task_gid, text='[wiki-researcher] Research stage completed \u2014 YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM')\n     e. Update Kiro_RW with pipeline state: append 'pipeline: research completed [date]'\n4. IF the research subtask is already completed: skip \u2014 research is done, task is waiting for Stage 2 (Draft).\n5. IF no research subtask exists at all: skip \u2014 this task may have been moved to In Progress manually or is in a later pipeline stage. Check for other pipeline subtasks (\u270f\ufe0f Draft, \ud83d\udd0d Review, \u2705 Approve) to determine current stage.\n\nNote: Only initiate research for tasks where the research subtask exists but is incomplete. The research subtask is created during triage (Step 3C above) \u2014 its existence signals the task has entered the pipeline. Its incompleteness signals research hasn't been done yet.\n\nSTEP 3E \u2014 DRAFT STAGE DETECTION (Stage 2 \u2014 wiki-writer):\nAfter research initiation, check for tasks where research is complete but draft hasn't started. This is how the pipeline advances from Stage 1 (Research) to Stage 2 (Draft).\n\nFor ALL tasks in the In Progress section (GID: 1213917923741223):\n1. Call GetSubtasksForTask(task_gid) to check for pipeline subtasks.\n2. Look for a subtask matching '\ud83d\udccb Research: [name]' that IS completed (completed === true) \u2014 research is done.\n3. Look for a subtask matching '\u270f\ufe0f Draft: [name]' \u2014 if one exists (completed or not), draft stage has already been initiated. Skip this task.\n4. IF research subtask is completed AND no draft subtask exists:\n   - This task needs Stage 2 (Draft) executed.\n   - VERIFY: Check that a pinned research comment exists on the task via GetTaskStories(task_gid). Look for a story with is_pinned=true. If no pinned comment exists, skip \u2014 research may not have posted its brief yet.\n   - INVOKE wiki-writer agent with the following context:\n     a. Task GID and task name\n     b. Task description (Richard's original idea from html_notes or notes)\n     c. Pinned research comment content (the research brief)\n     d. Kiro_RW field content (triage context, scope, pipeline state)\n     e. Work_Product type (from Kiro_RW triage entry)\n     f. Instruction: Load style guides before writing (richard-writing-style.md, richard-style-docs.md, richard-style-amazon.md)\n   - The wiki-writer will:\n     a. Read the pinned research comment and task description\n     b. Load Richard's style guides\n     c. Write a ~500w draft in html_notes using Asana HTML formatting (allowed tags only: body, strong, em, u, s, code, a, ul, ol, li)\n     d. Draft structure: bold title, executive summary (2-3 sentences), 3-5 bold-headed sections, Next Steps section\n     e. Create and complete the draft subtask: CreateTask(name='\u270f\ufe0f Draft: [parent task name]', parent=task_gid, assignee='1212732742544167', project='1213917352480610') then UpdateTask(subtask_gid, completed='true')\n     f. Move task to Review section: UpdateTask(task_gid, assignee_section='1213917923779848')\n     g. Log stage transition: CreateTaskStory(task_gid, text='[wiki-writer] Draft stage completed \u2014 YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM')\n     h. Update Kiro_RW: append 'pipeline: draft completed [date]'\n5. IF research subtask is NOT completed: skip \u2014 still in Stage 1 (Research). Step 3D handles this.\n6. IF draft subtask already exists: skip \u2014 draft stage already initiated or completed.\n\nNote: The draft goes into html_notes (the task description), NOT a comment. After drafting, the task moves from In Progress to Review. The wiki-critic (Stage 3) picks it up from there.\n\nSTEP 3F \u2014 REVIEW STAGE DETECTION (Stage 3 \u2014 wiki-critic):\nAfter draft detection, check for tasks in the Review section where the draft is complete but no review has been done yet. This is how the pipeline advances from Stage 2 (Draft) to Stage 3 (Review).\n\nFor ALL tasks in the Review section (GID: 1213917923779848):\n1. Call GetSubtasksForTask(task_gid) to check for pipeline subtasks.\n2. Look for a subtask matching '\u270f\ufe0f Draft: [name]' that IS completed (completed === true) \u2014 draft is done.\n3. Look for a subtask matching '\ud83d\udd0d Review: [name]' \u2014 if one exists (completed or not), review stage has already been initiated. Skip this task.\n4. IF draft subtask is completed AND no review subtask exists:\n   - This task needs Stage 3 (Review) executed.\n   - INVOKE wiki-critic agent with the following context:\n     a. Task GID and task name\n     b. The draft content from html_notes (read via GetTaskDetails)\n     c. The pinned research comment (read via GetTaskStories, find is_pinned=true)\n     d. Kiro_RW field content (pipeline state, triage context, consecutive_sub8 count if any)\n   - The wiki-critic will:\n     a. Read the draft from html_notes and the pinned research comment for context\n     b. Score on 5 dimensions: usefulness, clarity, accuracy, dual-audience, economy (each 1-10)\n     c. Compute the average score (arithmetic mean of all 5 dimensions)\n     d. Post review as a comment via CreateTaskStory(task_gid, html_text='<body>..review with scores and feedback..</body>')\n     e. Create and complete the review subtask: CreateTask(name='\ud83d\udd0d Review: [parent task name]', parent=task_gid, assignee='1212732742544167', project='1213917352480610') then UpdateTask(subtask_gid, completed='true')\n     f. DECISION based on average score:\n        - IF average >= 8 (APPROVE): Create Approval subtask: CreateTask(name='\u2705 Approve: [parent task name]', resource_subtype='approval', parent=task_gid, assignee='1212732742544167', project='1213917352480610'). Log: '[wiki-critic] Review completed \u2014 APPROVE (avg [N.N]/10). Approval subtask created.'\n        - IF average < 8 AND consecutive_sub8 < 2 (REVISE): Post revision notes as comment. Move task back to In Progress section (GID: 1213917923741223) for wiki-writer to revise. Update Kiro_RW with consecutive_sub8 count (increment or set to 1). Log: '[wiki-critic] Review completed \u2014 REVISE (avg [N.N]/10). Returning to wiki-writer.'\n        - IF average < 8 AND consecutive_sub8 >= 1 reaching 2 (ESCALATE): Do NOT return to Stage 2. Flag task for Richard in daily brief. Update Kiro_RW with consecutive_sub8=2 and FLAGGED FOR RICHARD. Log: '[wiki-critic] Review completed \u2014 ESCALATE (avg [N.N]/10). Two consecutive sub-8 scores \u2014 manual direction needed.'\n     g. Update Kiro_RW: append 'pipeline: review completed [date], score=[N.N]/10, verdict=[APPROVE/REVISE/ESCALATE]'\n5. IF draft subtask is NOT completed: skip \u2014 still in Stage 2 (Draft). Step 3E handles this.\n6. IF review subtask already exists: skip \u2014 review stage already initiated or completed.\n\nCONSECUTIVE SUB-8 TRACKING: The consecutive sub-8 count is stored in Kiro_RW as 'consecutive_sub8=N'. Before scoring, parse Kiro_RW for the most recent consecutive_sub8 value. On APPROVE: the counter resets (next review cycle starts fresh). On REVISE: increment the counter. When the counter reaches 2: ESCALATE \u2014 no third automatic revision attempt.\n\nNote: The 8/10 threshold is exact \u2014 not 7.9, not 8.1. The Approval subtask MUST use resource_subtype='approval'. The wiki-critic follows the ABPS AI review instructions in its agent definition for scoring rubric and review comment format.\n\nSTEP 3G \u2014 APPROVAL DETECTION (Stage 4 \u2014 Richard approves or rejects):\nAfter review stage detection, check for tasks in the Review section that have an Approval subtask. This is how the pipeline detects Richard's approval or rejection and advances from Stage 4 to Stage 5 (Expansion).\n\nFor ALL tasks in the Review section (GID: 1213917923779848):\n1. Call GetSubtasksForTask(task_gid) to check for pipeline subtasks.\n2. Look for a subtask with resource_subtype='approval' matching the pattern '\u2705 Approve: [name]'.\n3. IF no approval subtask exists: skip \u2014 this task hasn't reached Stage 4 yet (still in review or awaiting critic).\n4. IF approval subtask exists, check its completed field:\n\n   CASE A \u2014 APPROVED (completed === true):\n   Richard approved the draft by completing the approval subtask. Proceed to Stage 5 (Expansion).\n   a. READ CURRENT CONTENT FIRST (read-before-write pattern):\n      - Call GetTaskDetails(task_gid, opt_fields='name,html_notes,custom_fields.name,custom_fields.display_value') to read the current html_notes.\n      - Check if Richard has added any content since the last agent write (compare against Kiro_RW timestamps).\n      - If Richard added content: preserve it \u2014 integrate expansion around Richard's additions.\n   b. INVOKE wiki-writer agent for expansion with the following context:\n      - Task GID and task name\n      - Current html_notes content (the ~500w draft, plus any Richard additions)\n      - The pinned research comment (read via GetTaskStories, find is_pinned=true)\n      - Kiro_RW field content (full pipeline history)\n      - Work_Product type (from Kiro_RW triage entry)\n      - Instruction: Expand from ~500w to ~2000w. Load style guides (richard-writing-style.md, richard-style-docs.md, richard-style-amazon.md).\n      - Full document structure: bold title, executive summary, context section, detailed analysis sections with bold headers, supporting data/evidence, recommendations with reasoning, next steps with owners and dates.\n      - Use only allowed Asana HTML tags: body, strong, em, u, s, code, a, ul, ol, li.\n   c. CHECK FREQUENCY FIELD TO DETERMINE DESTINATION:\n      - Read the task's Frequency custom field (GID: 1213921303350613) from the GetTaskDetails result.\n      - Map the Frequency enum option GID to its cadence value:\n        - 1213921303350614 = one-time\n        - 1213921303350615 = weekly\n        - 1213921303350616 = monthly\n        - 1213921303350617 = quarterly\n\n      IF Frequency == 'one-time' (option GID 1213921303350614):\n        - ONE-TIME TASKS GO TO ARCHIVE, NOT ACTIVE.\n        - MOVE TASK TO ARCHIVE SECTION:\n          Call UpdateTask(task_gid, assignee_section='1213917833240629') to move to Archive.\n          VERIFICATION: Confirm via GetTaskDetails \u2192 memberships \u2192 section.gid should be '1213917833240629' (Archive).\n        - MARK TASK COMPLETED:\n          Call UpdateTask(task_gid, completed='true')\n        - DO NOT register in recurring-task-state.json \u2014 one-time tasks have no refresh cadence.\n        - LOG: CreateTaskStory(task_gid, text='[wiki-writer] Expansion completed \u2014 one-time work product archived and completed \u2014 YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM')\n        - UPDATE KIRO_RW: Append: 'pipeline: approved [date], expanded to ~2000w, one-time \u2192 moved to Archive, completed'\n\n      IF Frequency != 'one-time' (weekly, monthly, or quarterly):\n        - MOVE TASK TO ACTIVE SECTION:\n          Call UpdateTask(task_gid, assignee_section='1213917968512184') to move to Active.\n          VERIFICATION: Confirm via GetTaskDetails \u2192 memberships \u2192 section.gid should be '1213917968512184' (Active).\n        - REGISTER IN RECURRING-TASK-STATE.JSON:\n          Read ~/shared/context/active/recurring-task-state.json.\n          Add a new entry under the 'tasks' object with key 'abps_ai_{task_gid}' (e.g., 'abps_ai_1234567890123').\n          Entry format:\n          {\n            \"cadence\": \"[weekly|monthly|quarterly]\",\n            \"last_run\": \"YYYY-MM-DD\",\n            \"last_run_period\": \"[computed current period]\",\n            \"description\": \"ABPS AI: [task_name] \u2014 refresh work product\"\n          }\n          Period computation for last_run_period:\n          - weekly: format today as YYYY-WNN using ISO week number (e.g., 2026-W16)\n          - monthly: format today as YYYY-MM (e.g., 2026-04)\n          - quarterly: format today as YYYY-QN where Q1=Jan-Mar, Q2=Apr-Jun, Q3=Jul-Sep, Q4=Oct-Dec (e.g., 2026-Q2)\n          Write the updated JSON back to ~/shared/context/active/recurring-task-state.json.\n        - LOG: CreateTaskStory(task_gid, text='[wiki-writer] Expansion completed \u2014 registered for [cadence] refresh in recurring-task-state.json \u2014 YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM')\n        - UPDATE KIRO_RW: Append: 'pipeline: approved [date], expanded to ~2000w, moved to Active, registered for [cadence] refresh'\n\n   CASE B \u2014 PENDING, CHECK FOR REJECTION (completed === false):\n   The approval subtask is still open. Check if Richard posted feedback indicating rejection.\n   a. Get the approval subtask's created_at timestamp (from GetTaskDetails on the approval subtask).\n   b. Call GetTaskStories(task_gid) on the PARENT task to get all comments.\n   c. Look for comments from Richard (created_by.gid === '1212732742544167') that were posted AFTER the approval subtask's created_at timestamp.\n   d. IF Richard posted a comment after the approval subtask was created:\n      - This is a REJECTION \u2014 Richard provided feedback instead of completing the approval.\n      - Read Richard's comment text \u2014 this is the revision feedback.\n      - RETURN TO STAGE 2 (wiki-writer revises):\n        i. Move task back to In Progress section: UpdateTask(task_gid, assignee_section='1213917923741223')\n        ii. The existing '\ud83d\udd0d Review: [name]' subtask stays completed (it records the previous review cycle).\n        iii. Delete or complete the current approval subtask to clear the gate: UpdateTask(approval_subtask_gid, completed='true') \u2014 completing it clears it from Richard's view. A new approval subtask will be created after the next successful review.\n        iv. Log rejection: CreateTaskStory(task_gid, text='[AM-2] Rejection detected \u2014 Richard posted feedback. Returning to Stage 2 (wiki-writer revision). Reason: [first 100 chars of Richard comment]')\n        v. Update Kiro_RW: append 'pipeline: rejected [date], reason=[summary], returning to Stage 2'\n        vi. Reset consecutive_sub8 counter in Kiro_RW to 0 (Richard's feedback starts a fresh revision cycle).\n      - The task is now back in In Progress. On the next AM-2 run, Step 3E (Draft Stage Detection) will detect that the task needs a new draft cycle. The wiki-writer will read Richard's feedback comment and the existing html_notes to produce a revised draft.\n   e. IF no Richard comment exists after the approval subtask creation:\n      - Approval is still PENDING \u2014 Richard hasn't acted yet. Skip this task.\n      - No action needed. The task stays in Review awaiting Richard's decision.\n\nNote: Richard approves by COMPLETING the approval subtask (resource_subtype='approval'). Richard rejects by posting a COMMENT with feedback WITHOUT completing the approval subtask. The agent checks both signals during each AM-2 scan. The read-before-write pattern on html_notes is critical \u2014 never overwrite Richard's additions during expansion.\n\nSTEP 3H \u2014 DATE WINDOW CHECK (tasks entering their execution window):\nAfter pipeline stage processing, scan for triaged tasks whose Begin Date has arrived but haven't entered the pipeline yet. This catches tasks that were triaged with a future Begin Date and left in Intake \u2014 when their date window opens, they need to start the pipeline.\n\nThis step covers ALL ABPS AI tasks, not just those in a specific section. The filter:\n- start_on (Begin Date) <= today\n- completed === false\n- Section is NOT Active (GID: 1213917968512184)\n- Section is NOT Archive (GID: 1213917833240629)\n\nFor each task matching this filter:\n1. Call GetSubtasksForTask(task_gid) to check for existing pipeline subtasks.\n2. Look for ANY pipeline subtask: '\ud83d\udccb Research: [name]', '\u270f\ufe0f Draft: [name]', '\ud83d\udd0d Review: [name]', or '\u2705 Approve: [name]'.\n3. IF NO pipeline subtasks exist \u2014 this task is entering its date window for the FIRST TIME:\n   a. This task was triaged (has Routine set) but was left in Intake because its Begin Date was in the future. Now the date has arrived.\n   b. MOVE TASK TO IN PROGRESS SECTION:\n      - Call UpdateTask(task_gid, assignee_section='1213917923741223') to move to In Progress.\n      - VERIFICATION: Confirm via GetTaskDetails \u2192 memberships \u2192 section.gid should be '1213917923741223' (In Progress).\n   c. CREATE RESEARCH SUBTASK (pipeline entry point):\n      - Call: CreateTask(name='\ud83d\udccb Research: [parent task name]', parent=task_gid, assignee='1212732742544167', project='1213917352480610')\n      - This signals the task has entered the pipeline.\n   d. UPDATE KIRO_RW:\n      - Append: '[date] Date window opened \u2014 moved to In Progress, pipeline initiated.'\n   e. LOG: CreateTaskStory(task_gid, text='[AM-2] Date window opened (start_on <= today). Task moved to In Progress, research subtask created \u2014 YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM')\n   f. FLAG FOR DAILY BRIEF: Include this task in the AM-2 output as 'Entering pipeline today: [task name]'\n4. IF pipeline subtasks already exist: skip \u2014 the task is already in the pipeline. Steps 3D-3G handle pipeline progression.\n5. IMPORTANT: The agent SHALL NOT work on tasks whose Begin Date (start_on) is in the future. If start_on > today, skip the task entirely regardless of section. Future-dated tasks wait in Intake until their date window opens.\n\nNote: This step consolidates with Step 3C (which handles newly triaged tasks with begin date <= today) and Step 3D (which handles In Progress tasks with research subtasks). Step 3H catches the gap: tasks triaged earlier with a future begin date that are now ready. Together, these three steps ensure every task enters the pipeline exactly when its date window opens \u2014 no earlier, no later.\n\nSTEP 3I \u2014 NEAR-DUE ESCALATION (tasks approaching their Due Date):\nAfter the date window check, identify tasks that are running out of time. If a task's Due Date is within 2 calendar days and the work product hasn't reached Review yet, escalate it.\n\nFor ALL incomplete ABPS AI tasks (from the GetTasksFromProject results in Step 1):\n1. Check due_on (Due Date) against today's date.\n2. Compute days_until_due = due_on - today (in calendar days).\n3. IF days_until_due <= 2 AND days_until_due >= 0 (due within 2 calendar days, including today and tomorrow):\n   a. Check the task's section membership.\n   b. IF the task is NOT in the Review section (GID: 1213917923779848) AND NOT completed:\n      - This task is near-due and hasn't reached the review gate yet \u2014 it needs escalation.\n      - SET PRIORITY_RW TO TODAY:\n        Call UpdateTask(task_gid, custom_fields={'1212905889837829': '1212905889837830'})\n        This sets Priority_RW to 'Today' (option GID: 1212905889837830).\n      - UPDATE KIRO_RW:\n        Append: '[date] NEAR-DUE ESCALATION: Due in [N] day(s), not yet in Review. Priority_RW set to Today.'\n      - FLAG FOR DAILY BRIEF: Include in AM-2 output under a '\u26a0\ufe0f Near-Due ABPS Tasks' section:\n        '[task name] \u2014 due [due_on] ([N] day(s) remaining), currently in [section name]. Priority escalated to Today.'\n   c. IF the task IS in the Review section: skip \u2014 it's already in the review/approval gate, which is the expected path.\n   d. IF the task IS completed: skip.\n4. Tasks with due_on > today + 2 days: no escalation needed.\n5. Tasks with no due_on set: skip (no due date to check against).\n\nNote: The 2-day threshold is calendar days, not business days. If today is Friday and due_on is Sunday, that's 2 days \u2014 escalate. The escalation sets Priority_RW to Today so the task appears in Richard's Today view and gets attention in the daily brief. Tasks already in Review are excluded because they're in the approval pipeline \u2014 escalating them would be noise.\n\nSTEP 3J \u2014 OVERDUE FLAGGING (tasks past their Due Date):\nAfter near-due escalation, identify tasks that have blown past their Due Date without being approved.\n\nFor ALL incomplete ABPS AI tasks (from the GetTasksFromProject results in Step 1):\n1. Check due_on (Due Date) against today's date.\n2. IF due_on < today (Due Date is in the past) AND completed === false:\n   a. Check for an approved Approval subtask:\n      - Call GetSubtasksForTask(task_gid).\n      - Look for a subtask with resource_subtype='approval' AND completed === true.\n   b. IF an approved Approval subtask exists: skip \u2014 the work product was approved, it's just pending expansion or already active. Not truly overdue.\n   c. IF NO approved Approval subtask exists (either no approval subtask at all, or one exists but is not completed):\n      - This task is OVERDUE \u2014 past its Due Date without an approved work product.\n      - Compute days_overdue = today - due_on.\n      - WRITE KIRO_RW ENTRY with recommended action:\n        Append: '[date] OVERDUE ([days_overdue] days past due). Recommended action: (1) Extend due date if work is in progress and viable, (2) Reduce scope to ship a smaller deliverable by [new date], or (3) Kill the task if it's no longer relevant. Awaiting Richard's direction.'\n        Call UpdateTask(task_gid, custom_fields={'1213915851848087': [updated Kiro_RW text]})\n      - FLAG FOR DAILY BRIEF: Include in AM-2 output under a '\ud83d\udea8 Overdue ABPS Tasks' section:\n        '[task name] \u2014 due [due_on] ([days_overdue] days overdue), currently in [section name]. No approved work product. Recommended: extend / reduce scope / kill.'\n      - LOG: CreateTaskStory(task_gid, text='[AM-2] OVERDUE FLAG: Task is [days_overdue] days past due with no approved work product. Recommended actions: extend due date, reduce scope, or kill. \u2014 YYYY-MM-DD')\n3. Tasks with due_on >= today: not overdue (handled by Step 3I if near-due).\n4. Tasks with no due_on set: skip.\n5. Completed tasks: skip.\n\nNote: The overdue check specifically looks for the ABSENCE of an approved Approval subtask. A task in Active section with an approved subtask is not overdue \u2014 it's a living document. A task in In Progress or Review that's past its due date WITHOUT approval IS overdue and needs Richard's attention. The recommended actions (extend, reduce scope, kill) give Richard clear options rather than just flagging the problem.\n\nSTEP 3K \u2014 REFRESH CHECK (cadence-based refresh for Active living documents):\nAfter overdue flagging, check Active section tasks that have a recurring Frequency for refresh due dates. This is how the ABPS AI document factory keeps living documents current \u2014 weekly, monthly, or quarterly refreshes based on the task's Frequency field.\n\nFor ALL tasks in the Active section (GID: 1213917968512184):\n1. Call GetTaskDetails(task_gid, opt_fields='name,html_notes,custom_fields.name,custom_fields.display_value') to read the task's Frequency field.\n2. Read the Frequency custom field (GID: 1213921303350613). Map the enum option GID:\n   - 1213921303350614 = one-time \u2192 SKIP this task entirely. One-time tasks should not be in Active (they go to Archive after expansion). If found here, flag as anomaly in AM-2 output.\n   - 1213921303350615 = weekly\n   - 1213921303350616 = monthly\n   - 1213921303350617 = quarterly\n3. IF Frequency is weekly, monthly, or quarterly:\n   a. Read ~/shared/context/active/recurring-task-state.json.\n   b. Look for an entry with key 'abps_ai_{task_gid}' in the 'tasks' object.\n   c. IF NO ENTRY EXISTS: This task was moved to Active before the registration logic was added, or registration failed. Register it now:\n      - Add entry: { \"cadence\": \"[weekly|monthly|quarterly]\", \"last_run\": null, \"last_run_period\": null, \"description\": \"ABPS AI: [task_name] \u2014 refresh work product\" }\n      - Write updated JSON back to recurring-task-state.json.\n      - The null last_run_period will trigger a refresh on this run (null != current_period).\n   d. COMPUTE CURRENT PERIOD based on cadence and today's date:\n      - weekly: format today as YYYY-WNN using ISO week number. Example: 2026-04-15 \u2192 2026-W16. Use ISO 8601 week numbering (Monday is first day of week, W01 contains the year's first Thursday).\n      - monthly: format today as YYYY-MM. Example: 2026-04-15 \u2192 2026-04.\n      - quarterly: format today as YYYY-QN where Q1=Jan(01)-Mar(03), Q2=Apr(04)-Jun(06), Q3=Jul(07)-Sep(09), Q4=Oct(10)-Dec(12). Example: 2026-04-15 \u2192 2026-Q2.\n   e. COMPARE last_run_period (from recurring-task-state.json) against current_period:\n      - IF last_run_period === current_period: refresh is NOT due. Skip this task.\n      - IF last_run_period !== current_period (or last_run_period is null): refresh IS DUE.\n   f. EXECUTE REFRESH (when due):\n      i. READ CURRENT CONTENT (read-before-write):\n         - The html_notes from GetTaskDetails (already read in step 1) contains the current work product.\n         - Check if Richard has added content since the last refresh (compare against Kiro_RW timestamps).\n         - If Richard added content: preserve it \u2014 integrate refresh updates around Richard's additions.\n      ii. INVOKE wiki-researcher for fresh context:\n         - Pass: task GID, task name, current html_notes content, Kiro_RW field content\n         - The wiki-researcher gathers fresh data from: body system organs, DuckDB (ps-analytics), recent Slack signals, Outlook email, web search\n         - The researcher posts a refresh research brief as a comment (NOT pinned \u2014 pinned comment is the original research): CreateTaskStory(task_gid, html_text='<body><strong>Refresh Research Brief \u2014 YYYY-MM-DD</strong>..fresh context..</body>')\n      iii. INVOKE wiki-writer to update the work product:\n         - Pass: task GID, task name, current html_notes, refresh research comment, Kiro_RW, style guides\n         - Instruction: Update the existing ~2000w document with current information, improvements, or corrections. Do NOT rewrite from scratch \u2014 update in place.\n         - Load style guides: richard-writing-style.md, richard-style-docs.md, richard-style-amazon.md\n         - The wiki-writer will:\n           a. Read the current html_notes and the refresh research comment\n           b. Update sections with current data, fix outdated information, add new insights\n           c. ADD DATED REVISION LINE near the top of the document (after the title, before Executive Summary):\n              <strong>Updated YYYY-MM-DD: [brief description of what changed]</strong>\n              Example: <strong>Updated 2026-04-15: Refreshed AU market metrics with Q2 data, added new competitor analysis</strong>\n           d. Write updated html_notes via UpdateTask(task_gid, html_notes=...)\n           e. Use only allowed Asana HTML tags: body, strong, em, u, s, code, a, ul, ol, li\n      iv. POST REFRESH COMMENT:\n         - CreateTaskStory(task_gid, text='\ud83d\udd04 Refresh completed: [summary of what was updated]. Cadence: [cadence]. Next refresh: [next period]. \u2014 YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM')\n      v. UPDATE RECURRING-TASK-STATE.JSON:\n         - Read ~/shared/context/active/recurring-task-state.json\n         - Update the 'abps_ai_{task_gid}' entry:\n           - last_run: today's date (YYYY-MM-DD)\n           - last_run_period: current_period (the period string computed in step d)\n         - Write updated JSON back to the file.\n      vi. UPDATE KIRO_RW:\n         - Append: '[date] REFRESH completed ([cadence]). Period: [current_period]. Changes: [brief summary].'\n      vii. FLAG FOR DAILY BRIEF: Include in AM-2 output under a '\ud83d\udd04 Refreshed ABPS Documents' section:\n         '[task name] \u2014 [cadence] refresh completed. Updated: [what changed].'\n4. After processing all Active tasks, compile the refresh summary for Step 4 output.\n\nPERIOD COMPUTATION REFERENCE (used in both registration and refresh check):\n- Weekly: YYYY-WNN \u2014 ISO 8601 week number. Week 1 contains the year's first Thursday. Monday is the first day of the week. Examples: 2026-01-01 \u2192 2026-W01, 2026-12-31 \u2192 2026-W53 or 2027-W01 depending on year.\n- Monthly: YYYY-MM \u2014 Simple year-month. Examples: 2026-01-15 \u2192 2026-01, 2026-12-01 \u2192 2026-12.\n- Quarterly: YYYY-QN \u2014 Q1=Jan/Feb/Mar (months 01-03), Q2=Apr/May/Jun (months 04-06), Q3=Jul/Aug/Sep (months 07-09), Q4=Oct/Nov/Dec (months 10-12). Examples: 2026-01-15 \u2192 2026-Q1, 2026-04-15 \u2192 2026-Q2, 2026-07-01 \u2192 2026-Q3, 2026-10-31 \u2192 2026-Q4.\n\nNote: The refresh check is the LAST pipeline step before the output summary (Step 4). It runs after all pipeline stages (3D-3G), date window checks (3H), near-due escalation (3I), and overdue flagging (3J). This ensures that Active documents are refreshed only after all pipeline work is processed. One-time tasks should never appear in Active \u2014 they go to Archive after expansion (see Step 3G Case A). If a one-time task is found in Active, flag it as an anomaly.\n\nSTEP 4 \u2014 INCLUDE IN AM-2 OUTPUT:\nAfter presenting triage decisions and running all checks (Steps 3H-3J), include ABPS AI status summary in the day overview:\n- Intake: [N] tasks ([M] untriaged, [K] awaiting date window)\n- In Progress: [list task names + pipeline stage]\n- Review: [list task names awaiting approval]\n- Active: [N] living documents\n- Archive: [N] completed\n- \ud83c\udd95 Entering pipeline today: [list tasks whose date window just opened \u2014 from Step 3H]\n- \u26a0\ufe0f Near-Due ABPS Tasks: [list tasks due within 2 days not yet in Review \u2014 from Step 3I]\n- \ud83d\udea8 Overdue ABPS Tasks: [list tasks past due without approved work product \u2014 from Step 3J, with recommended actions]\n- \ud83d\udd04 Refreshed ABPS Documents: [list tasks refreshed this run \u2014 from Step 3K, with summary of changes]\n- \ud83d\udcc5 Refresh Due This Period: [list Active tasks with refresh due but not yet executed \u2014 from Step 3K, if any were skipped due to errors]\n- Upcoming this week: [tasks with start_on within next 7 days that haven't entered pipeline yet]\n\nKEY GIDS FOR ABPS AI - Content:\n- Project: 1213917352480610\n- Intake section: 1213917352480612\n- In Progress section: 1213917923741223\n- Review section: 1213917923779848\n- Active section: 1213917968512184\n- Archive section: 1213917833240629\n- Routine field: 1213608836755502\n- Priority_RW field: 1212905889837829\n- Kiro_RW field: 1213915851848087\n- Frequency field: 1213921303350613\n- Richard's GID: 1212732742544167\n\nPHASE 1C \u2014 PORTFOLIO PROJECT SCAN:\nScan all portfolio child projects for Richard's tasks. Apply the same enrichment, date management, and guardrail rules as Phase 1 Enhancement and Phase 1B. Reference asana-command-center.md \u00a7 Portfolio Projects for all GIDs, sections, custom fields, recurring patterns, and event calendar.\n\nGUARDRAIL PROTOCOL (applies to ALL portfolio writes):\nSame as Phase 1B: PRE-WRITE assignee check (gid === '1212732742544167'), AUDIT LOG every write to ~/shared/context/active/asana-audit-log.jsonl with project field (AU, MX, WW_Testing, WW_Acquisition, Paid_App), READ-BEFORE-WRITE for html_notes, API FAILURE \u2192 log \u2192 retry once after 2s \u2192 flag if retry fails.\n\nSTEP 1 \u2014 PORTFOLIO DISCOVERY:\n- Call GetPortfolioItems(portfolio_gid='1212775592612914') \u2192 ABIX PS children (AU, MX).\n- Call GetPortfolioItems(portfolio_gid='1212762061512816') \u2192 ABPS children.\n- Also include managed projects outside portfolio hierarchy: WW Testing (1205997667578893), WW Acquisition (1206011235630048), Paid App (1205997667578886).\n- For each project returned, compare against known projects in asana-command-center.md \u00a7 Portfolio Projects.\n- IF a new project appears not in the command center:\n  \u2192 Call GetProjectSections(project_gid) to discover sections.\n  \u2192 Call GetTaskDetails on a sample task for custom field discovery.\n  \u2192 Flag for Richard: 'New project detected in [portfolio]: [name]. GIDs recorded.'\n  \u2192 Update asana-command-center.md \u00a7 Portfolio Projects with new project profile.\n\nSTEP 2 \u2014 PER-PROJECT TASK SCAN:\nFor each active project (AU: 1212762061512767, MX: 1212775592612917, WW Testing: 1205997667578893, WW Acq: 1206011235630048, Paid App: 1205997667578886):\n- Call GetTasksFromProject(project_gid, opt_fields='name,assignee.gid,due_on,start_on,completed,completed_at,custom_fields.name,custom_fields.display_value,custom_fields.gid,memberships.section.name,memberships.section.gid').\n- For each task, check assignee.gid:\n  - IF === '1212732742544167' (Richard): process for enrichment, dates, and automation.\n  - IF !== Richard: this is a Cross_Team_Task. Read-only \u2014 used for blocker detection (Step 7). Never write.\n- Skip completed tasks for enrichment. Note recently completed tasks for recurring detection (Step 6).\n\nSTEP 3 \u2014 FIELD ENRICHMENT CHECK:\nFor each of Richard's incomplete tasks in the project, apply the same four enrichment rules as Phase 1 Enhancement:\na. KIRO_RW (GID: 1213915851848087): If empty or non-brevity \u2192 propose M/D: <10 words entry.\nb. NEXT ACTION (GID: 1213921400039514): If empty \u2192 propose imperative <15 words.\nc. DATES: If due_on set but start_on null \u2192 propose start_on = max(today, due_on - 7).\nd. PRIORITY_RW (GID: 1212905889837829): If Routine set but Priority_RW null \u2192 propose 'Not urgent' (GID: 1212905889837833).\nQueue all proposals for portfolio enrichment batch (Step 11).\n\nSTEP 4 \u2014 DATE WINDOW CHECKS:\nFor each of Richard's incomplete tasks, check terminal section exclusion first. Terminal sections per project (from command center):\n- AU: (none \u2014 no Complete/Done section)\n- MX: (none \u2014 no Complete/Done section)\n- WW Testing: Complete (1205997667578902)\n- WW Acq: Complete (1206011240457091)\n- Paid App: Complete (1205997667578889)\nTasks in terminal sections: skip all date checks below. Still count in task totals.\n\na. NEAR-DUE ESCALATION:\n   IF due_on is set AND (due_on - today) is 0, 1, or 2 days AND NOT completed AND NOT in terminal section:\n   \u2192 BUDGET EXCEPTION: If task name matches budget keywords (budget, PO, spend, invoice, reconciliation, actuals, forecast), use 3-day threshold instead of 2. So budget tasks with (due_on - today) = 0, 1, 2, or 3 \u2192 escalate.\n   \u2192 Auto-set Priority_RW to Today: UpdateTask(task_gid, custom_fields={'1212905889837829': '1212905889837830'})\n   \u2192 Update Kiro_RW: 'M/D: Near-due. Priority escalated.'\n   \u2192 Update Next action with specific completion instruction referencing due date.\n   \u2192 AUDIT: Log with project identifier. Near-due escalation is automatic (safety measure, no approval needed).\n\nb. OVERDUE FLAGGING:\n   IF due_on < today AND NOT completed AND NOT in terminal section:\n   \u2192 Flag in findings. Do NOT auto-extend, auto-complete, or auto-change scope.\n   \u2192 Update Kiro_RW: 'M/D: Overdue [N]d. Extend or close.' where N = days overdue.\n   \u2192 Update Next action: 'Decide: extend due date, reduce scope, or complete'\n   \u2192 BUDGET EXCEPTION: If budget task is overdue, flag as CRITICAL (higher visibility than standard overdue).\n   \u2192 AUDIT: Log with project identifier.\n\nSTEP 5 \u2014 STATUS UPDATE STALENESS:\nFor each portfolio project, call GetStatusUpdatesFromObject(project_gid).\n- Parse created_at from the most recent status update.\n- IF no status updates exist \u2192 flag as 'never updated' in findings.\n- IF today - created_at > 14 days \u2192 flag as Stale_Status. (Exactly 14 days = NOT stale.)\n- Extract resource_subtype (health color: on_track=\ud83d\udfe2, at_risk=\ufffd\ufffd, off_track=\ud83d\udd34) from latest update.\n- Record: project name, health color, last update date, stale flag.\n\nSTEP 6 \u2014 RECURRING TASK AUTO-CREATION (AU + MX):\nAfter scanning each AU/MX project, check for recently completed tasks matching recurring patterns from asana-command-center.md \u00a7 Recurring Task Patterns.\n\nDetection: completed tasks whose names contain recurring keywords:\n- AU keywords: Weekly, Reporting, Agenda, MBR, Bi-monthly, Flash\n- MX keywords: Weekly, Reporting, WBR, MBR, Bi-monthly, Flash, Kingpin\n\nFor each detected completed recurring task:\na. COMPUTE next dates based on cadence (from command center tables):\n   - Weekly: due_on = prev_due_on + 7d; start_on = due_on - 2d\n   - Bi-monthly: due_on = prev_due_on + 14d; start_on = due_on - 3d\n   - Monthly: due_on = same day next month; start_on = due_on - 5d\nb. CREATE next instance:\n   CreateTask(name=[same task name], assignee='1212732742544167', project=[same project_gid], due_on=[computed], start_on=[computed])\n   Copy fields from completed task: Routine, section membership, project-specific custom fields.\n   - AU fields to copy: AU Priority (1212762061512785), Task Progress (1212762061512790)\n   - MX fields to copy: MX Priority (1212775592612935), MX Task Progress (1212762061512741)\n   Set Kiro_RW: 'M/D: Auto-created from completed instance.'\n   Set Priority_RW: 'Not urgent' (escalates as due date approaches).\nc. PRESENT to Richard: '\ud83d\udd04 Auto-created next [task name] due [date]. Approve?'\n   If Richard rejects \u2192 delete the created task.\nd. AUDIT: Log creation with project identifier.\n\nSTEP 7 \u2014 CROSS-TEAM BLOCKER DETECTION (MX):\nMX has cross-team dependencies. During the MX scan, read ALL tasks including Cross_Team_Tasks.\n\na. IDENTIFY teammate tasks that are overdue: due_on < today AND NOT completed AND assignee.gid !== '1212732742544167'.\nb. CORRELATE with Richard's tasks:\n   - Check subtask parent-child relationships.\n   - Check task name cross-references (e.g., shared keywords between teammate task and Richard's task).\n   - Check same-section proximity (tasks in same section likely related).\nc. IF correlated blocker confirmed:\n   \u2192 Update Richard's blocked task Kiro_RW: 'M/D: Blocked on [teammate] task. [N]d overdue.'\n   \u2192 Update Richard's blocked task Next_Action: 'Follow up with [teammate] on [blocker task name]'\n   \u2192 AUDIT: Log Kiro_RW and Next_Action writes on Richard's task.\nd. NEVER write to teammate tasks. Read-only for blocker detection.\ne. Surface all blockers in findings:\n   \u26a0\ufe0f CROSS-TEAM BLOCKERS (MX):\n   - [Teammate task name] (assigned to [name]) \u2014 [N] days overdue\n     Blocking: [Richard's task name] (due [date])\n     Suggested action: Follow up with [teammate] via Slack\n\nSTEP 8 \u2014 EVENT COUNTDOWN AUTOMATION (Paid App):\nRead the event calendar from asana-command-center.md \u00a7 Event Calendar (Paid App). For each event:\n- Compute days until event from today.\n- IF event is within its prep window: scan Paid App tasks whose names match event keywords (case-insensitive).\n\na. ESCALATION RULES:\n   - Task in Backlog (1206020650712110) AND event within prep window \u2192 propose move to Prioritized (1205997667578887).\n   - Task in Prioritized (1205997667578887) AND event within escalation trigger window \u2192 propose move to In progress (1205997667578888) + set Priority_RW to Today.\n   - Task in Blocked (1205997667578890) AND event within escalation trigger window \u2192 flag as CRITICAL blocker in findings.\n\nb. STALE TASK TRIAGE (Paid App):\n   For tasks where due_on < today - 30 days AND NOT completed:\n   - Classify: event-related (name matches past event keyword) \u2192 recommend Archive.\n   - Classify: budget-related (name matches budget keywords) \u2192 recommend extend due date or escalate.\n   - Classify: other \u2192 recommend kill-or-revive decision.\n   Present batch to Richard:\n   \ud83e\uddf9 STALE TASK TRIAGE (Paid App) \u2014 [N] tasks need decisions:\n   For each: [task name] \u2014 [N]d overdue. Recommendation: [Archive/Extend/Kill-or-revive]. Reason: [why].\n\nc. PROMO EVENT TEMPLATE:\n   IF a new Paid App task is detected with an event keyword in the name AND has no subtasks:\n   \u2192 Propose standardized subtask structure:\n     \ud83d\udccb Campaign brief, \ud83d\udcb0 Budget confirmation, \ud83c\udfa8 Creative assets, \ud83d\udd27 Campaign build, \ud83d\udcca Post-event analysis\n   \u2192 Each subtask gets due dates relative to event date (brief: event-30d, budget: event-21d, creative: event-14d, build: event-7d, analysis: event+7d).\n   \u2192 Present to Richard for approval before creating.\n\nSTEP 9 \u2014 BUDGET/PO TRACKING (MX + Paid App):\nClassify Budget_Tasks across MX and Paid App by keyword match: budget, PO, spend, invoice, reconciliation, actuals, forecast.\n\na. Budget tasks use 3-day near-due threshold (not standard 2). Already handled in Step 4a budget exception.\nb. Overdue budget tasks flagged as CRITICAL. Already handled in Step 4b budget exception.\nc. MONTHLY ACTUALS CHECK (Paid App): If a 'monthly actuals' task approaches due date, check for a corresponding Brandon update task in the project. If missing \u2192 propose creating one assigned to Richard with due_on = actuals due_on - 2d.\nd. Record all active budget tasks for findings presentation.\n\nSTEP 10 \u2014 MARKET CONTEXT AUTO-REFRESH:\nAfter scanning each project, compile a project summary: active task count, overdue count, near-due count, current blockers, upcoming deadlines (next 7d), recent completions (last 7d), recurring task status, budget task status.\n\na. Compare compiled summary against current Context_Task content (pinned context tasks from command center):\n   - AU: 1213917747438931\n   - MX: 1213917639688517\n   - WW Testing: 1213917851621567\n   - WW Acq: 1213917771203342\n   - Paid App: 1213917771155873\nb. IF Material_Change detected (overdue count change, new blocker, task completion, near-due escalation, budget status change):\n   \u2192 READ-BEFORE-WRITE: GetTaskDetails(context_task_gid, opt_fields='html_notes') first. Preserve any content Richard added.\n   \u2192 UpdateTask(context_task_gid, html_notes='<body>..updated summary..</body>')\n   \u2192 Use only allowed HTML tags: body, strong, em, ul, ol, li, a, code.\n   \u2192 AUDIT: Log with project identifier.\nc. IF no Material_Change \u2192 skip update (avoid noise).\nd. REFRESH CADENCE: AU and MX context tasks refresh daily. WW Testing, WW Acq, Paid App refresh weekly (skip if last refresh was <7 days ago based on Kiro_RW timestamp on context task).\n\nSTEP 11 \u2014 PRESENT PORTFOLIO FINDINGS:\nAfter all projects are scanned, present unified findings to Richard:\n\n\ud83d\udcca PORTFOLIO SCAN \u2014 [N] projects scanned:\n\nABIX PS:\n- AU: [task_count] tasks ([overdue] overdue, [near_due] near-due) | Health: [\ud83d\udfe2/\ud83d\udfe1/\ud83d\udd34] (updated [date]) [\u26a0\ufe0f STALE if applicable]\n- MX: [task_count] tasks ([overdue] overdue, [near_due] near-due) | Health: [\ud83d\udfe2/\ud83d\udfe1/\ud83d\udd34] (updated [date]) [\u26a0\ufe0f STALE if applicable]\n\nManaged Projects:\n- WW Testing: [task_count] tasks ([overdue] overdue, [near_due] near-due) | Health: [\ud83d\udfe2/\ud83d\udfe1/\ud83d\udd34] (updated [date]) [\u26a0\ufe0f STALE if applicable]\n- WW Acquisition: [task_count] tasks ([overdue] overdue, [near_due] near-due) | Health: [\ud83d\udfe2/\ud83d\udfe1/\ud83d\udd34] (updated [date]) [\u26a0\ufe0f STALE if applicable]\n- Paid App: [task_count] tasks ([overdue] overdue, [near_due] near-due) | Health: [\ud83d\udfe2/\ud83d\udfe1/\ud83d\udd34] (updated [date]) [\u26a0\ufe0f STALE if applicable]\n\n\ud83d\udcdd PORTFOLIO ENRICHMENT \u2014 [N] task(s) need field updates:\nGroup by project. For each task with gaps:\n- [project] > [task name] (GID: [gid])\n  - Kiro_RW: [proposed] (currently: [empty or value])\n  - Next action: [proposed] (currently: empty)\n  - Begin Date: [proposed] (currently: unset)\n  - Priority_RW: Not urgent (currently: empty)\nACTION: Approve all, approve individually, or skip?\n\n\u26a0\ufe0f PORTFOLIO ALERTS:\n- Near-due: [task list with project context and due dates]\n- Overdue: [task list with project context and days overdue]\n- Stale projects: [project list with days since last update]\n- Cross-team blockers: [blocker list from Step 7]\n- Budget alerts: [budget task list with status and due dates]\n\n\ud83d\udcb0 BUDGET TASKS:\n- [MX/Paid App] [task name] \u2014 due [date] ([status: on track/near-due/overdue/critical])\n\n\ud83d\udd04 RECURRING TASK PROPOSALS:\nFor each auto-created recurring task from Step 6:\n- [project] > [task name] \u2014 next due [date]. Approve or reject?\n\n\ud83e\uddf9 STALE TASK TRIAGE (if any from Step 8b):\n- [task name] \u2014 [N]d overdue. Recommendation: [action]. Reason: [why].\n\nEXECUTE APPROVED PORTFOLIO ENRICHMENTS:\nFor each approved task, build UpdateTask with all approved fields in a single call (same pattern as Phase 1 Enhancement).\n- Combine Kiro_RW + Next action + Priority_RW into custom_fields object.\n- Include start_on only if due_on exists.\n- AUDIT: Log each write with correct project identifier (AU, MX, WW_Testing, WW_Acquisition, Paid_App).\n- API FAILURE: On failure \u2192 log \u2192 retry once after 2s \u2192 if retry fails, skip task and flag in daily brief.\n\nKEY GIDS FOR PORTFOLIO SCAN (quick reference \u2014 full details in asana-command-center.md):\n- ABIX PS portfolio: 1212775592612914\n- ABPS portfolio: 1212762061512816\n- AU: 1212762061512767 | MX: 1212775592612917\n- WW Testing: 1205997667578893 | WW Acq: 1206011235630048 | Paid App: 1205997667578886\n- Richard: 1212732742544167\n- Kiro_RW: 1213915851848087 | Next action: 1213921400039514 | Priority_RW: 1212905889837829\n- Priority_RW Today option: 1212905889837830 | Not urgent option: 1212905889837833\n- Routine: 1213608836755502 | Begin Date: 1213440376528542\n\nSNAPSHOT POPULATION \u2014 MORNING SNAPSHOT UPDATE:\nAfter Phase 1 Enhancement and Phase 1C complete, update ~/shared/context/active/asana-morning-snapshot.json with enrichment and portfolio data.\n\n1. MY_TASKS_ENRICHMENT SECTION:\n   Add or update the 'my_tasks_enrichment' key in the snapshot JSON:\n   {\n     \"my_tasks_enrichment\": {\n       \"total_incomplete\": <count of all incomplete My Tasks>,\n       \"missing_kiro_rw\": <count of tasks with empty/non-brevity Kiro_RW>,\n       \"missing_next_action\": <count of tasks with empty Next action>,\n       \"missing_routine\": <count of tasks with no Routine set>,\n       \"missing_dates\": <count of tasks with due_on but no start_on>,\n       \"enrichment_coverage_pct\": <percentage of tasks with all fields populated>\n     }\n   }\n   Compute enrichment_coverage_pct as: (tasks with Kiro_RW AND Next_action AND dates) / total_incomplete * 100, rounded to 1 decimal.\n\n2. PORTFOLIO_PROJECTS SECTION:\n   Add or update the 'portfolio_projects' key in the snapshot JSON:\n   {\n     \"portfolio_projects\": {\n       \"abix_ps\": {\n         \"au\": {\n           \"richard_task_count\": <count of Richard's incomplete tasks>,\n           \"overdue_count\": <count of overdue tasks>,\n           \"near_due_count\": <count of near-due tasks (0-2 days)>,\n           \"missing_fields_count\": <count of tasks missing Kiro_RW or Next_action>,\n           \"last_status_update\": \"YYYY-MM-DD or null\",\n           \"status_health\": \"green|yellow|red|unknown\",\n           \"status_stale\": true|false\n         },\n         \"mx\": { <same structure> }\n       },\n       \"managed_projects\": {\n         \"ww_testing\": { <same structure> },\n         \"ww_acquisition\": { <same structure> },\n         \"paid_app\": { <same structure> }\n       }\n     }\n   }\n   Populate from Phase 1C scan results. status_stale = true if last_status_update > 14 days ago or never updated.\n\nWrite the updated JSON back to ~/shared/context/active/asana-morning-snapshot.json, preserving all existing fields (bucket_counts, today_tasks, overdue_tasks, etc.).\n\nPHASE 2 \u2014 CURATE THE DAY (the morning ritual):\nThis is the core of the morning routine. Organize Richard's day into the four blocks, just like always. The agent curates, Richard approves and adjusts.\n\nSTEP 1 \u2014 BUILD THE DAY PLAN:\nPull all tasks with Priority_RW=Today from AM-1 data. Organize into the four blocks:\n- \ud83e\uddf9 Sweep (cap 5): Quick unblocking \u2014 send, confirm, triage. Low friction, high velocity.\n- \ud83c\udfaf Core (cap 4): Deep work \u2014 test designs, frameworks, stakeholder docs. THE HARD THING lives here.\n- \u2699\ufe0f Engine Room (cap 6): Hands-on \u2014 campaign builds, keyword changes, bids, spreadsheets.\n- \ud83d\udccb Admin (cap 3): Wind-down \u2014 budget, POs, invoices, compliance, goal updates.\n\nFor EACH task, enrich with:\n- NAME + due date + days overdue + project\n- CONTEXT: Pull from Kiro_RW field, task description, subtask status, recent comments (GetTaskStories last 3), and any related Slack signals from intake/. Summarize in 1-2 sentences: what's the current state of this task?\n- SUGGESTED NEXT ACTION: Based on context, what's the single concrete next step? Examples: 'Draft the outline', 'Reply to Megan's comment', 'Pull the data from Quip', 'Schedule the DDD', 'Mark complete \u2014 already done'.\n- DRAFT (if communication-related): If the task involves sending, replying, confirming, or following up \u2014 pre-draft the message in Richard's voice (load richard-writing-style.md). For Slack tasks, draft the Slack message. For email tasks, draft the email body. For comment/reply tasks, draft the Asana comment. Present the draft inline so Richard can approve, edit, or skip.\n- BLOCKERS: If Kiro_RW or Slack signals mention a blocker, surface it: 'Blocked by [who/what] since [date]'.\n- SUBTASK PROGRESS: If task has subtasks, show X/Y complete. Flag any overdue subtasks.\n\nSTEP 2 \u2014 IDENTIFY THE HARD THING:\nLook at Core tasks. Which one is the most important, most avoided, or most strategic? Propose it as THE HARD THING. If multiple Core tasks compete, ask Richard which one gets the slot.\n\nSTEP 3 \u2014 ENFORCE CAPS:\nIf any bucket exceeds its cap, propose demotions. Lowest-priority tasks (by Priority_RW, then due date) get flagged: 'Sweep has 7 (cap 5) \u2014 demote these 2 to Backlog?'\n\nSTEP 4 \u2014 TRIAGE UNTRIAGED:\nTasks with Priority_RW=Today but no Routine need a block assignment. Propose Routine based on task name, project, and Kiro_RW context. Tasks with no Priority_RW and no Routine that are due within 3 days \u2014 flag for decision.\n\nSTEP 5 \u2014 SURFACE SIGNALS:\n- Overdue tasks: 'X is N days overdue \u2014 do today, delegate, or kill?'\n- Activity signals from intake/asana-activity.md: comments needing response, due date changes, reassignments.\n- Stale tasks: 'No activity on Y in 14 days \u2014 still relevant?'\n- Due date conflicts: 'Multiple Core tasks due today \u2014 which is the hard thing?'\n\nSTEP 6 \u2014 PRESENT THE CURATED DAY:\nShow the final day plan as a clean board:\n\ud83e\uddf9 Sweep (X/5): [ordered task list]\n\ud83c\udfaf Core (X/4): [ordered task list \u2014 HARD THING marked with \u2b50]\n\u2699\ufe0f Engine Room (X/6): [ordered task list]\n\ud83d\udccb Admin (X/3): [ordered task list]\n\u26a0\ufe0f Overdue: [count + oldest]\n\ud83d\udce6 Needs triage: [count]\nTotal Today: X/18\n\nThen WAIT for Richard's directions.\n\nPHASE 3 \u2014 COMMAND CENTER (interactive):\nRichard adjusts the curated day. Execute every direction immediately against Asana. This is hands-on task management \u2014 not just flagging, but doing.\n\nEXECUTE Richard's directions using Asana MCP tools:\n- Move tasks between Routine buckets: UpdateTask(custom_fields={'1213608836755502': 'GID'}) \u2014 Sweep=1213608836755503, Core=1213608836755504, Engine Room=1213608836755505, Admin=1213608836755506\n- Change due dates: UpdateTask(due_on='YYYY-MM-DD')\n- Change priority: UpdateTask(custom_fields={'1212905889837829': 'GID'}) \u2014 Today=1212905889837830, Urgent=1212905889837831, Not urgent=1212905889837833\n- Create new tasks: CreateTask(name, assignee=1212732742544167, project, custom_fields, due_on)\n- Write/update task descriptions: UpdateTask(notes='text') or UpdateTask(html_notes='<body>...')\n- Add comments: CreateTaskStory(task_gid, text='...') or html_text for rich text\n- Complete tasks: UpdateTask(completed=true)\n- Create subtasks: CreateTask(parent=task_gid, name, ...)\n- Set importance: UpdateTask(custom_fields={'1212905889837865': '1212905889837866'})\n\nKeep executing until Richard says done or moves on. Every change is immediate against Asana.\n\nPHASE 4 \u2014 CONTEXT WRITES:\n- KIRO_RW: For each task triaged, write via UpdateTask custom_fields={'1213915851848087': 'M/D: <10 words max>'}. Follow brevity rule in asana-command-center.md \u00a7 5. Example: '4/3: Triaged. Core, quarterly, guide.'\n- NEXT ACTION: For each task touched, set Next action field via UpdateTask custom_fields={'1213921400039514': '<specific next step under 15 words>'}. Example: 'Draft 500w keyword strategy guide from research brief'.\n- TASK DESCRIPTIONS: For Today tasks with empty descriptions, populate with structured format via UpdateTask(html_notes): STATUS (current state), WHAT TO DO (next action), KEY DETAILS (project, due, blockers, related items), WHY IT MATTERS (Five Levels alignment). Present to Richard before writing.\n- SUBTASK NEXT-UP: For tasks with subtasks, if the next incomplete subtask is clear, note it in Kiro_RW as the suggested next action.\n- Update hands.md Priority Actions from final Asana state (include blocker registry: task, blocker, owner, days blocked).\n- Update rw-tracker.md, amcc streak. Archive intake.\n\nPHASE 5 \u2014 DRAFT REPLIES:\nNEVER email_reply/send/forward. Only email_draft. DEDUP drafts. Read thread, check memory.md tone, draft in Richard's voice. ASANA CONTEXT IN EMAIL: When drafting a reply that relates to an Asana task (detected by matching task name, project, or person to email subject/sender), include the task's current status and next action from Kiro_RW in the draft context. Example: if replying about 'Testing Document for Kate' and the Asana task shows 'Blocked on Megan's input, next action: follow up Thursday', weave that context into the reply naturally. Don't expose Asana field names \u2014 just use the information. Present for confirmation.\n\nREPORT: Tasks changed (created/updated/completed/flagged), command center actions taken, ABPS AI intake scan results (untriaged count, triage decisions presented, pipeline status summary), drafts created, streak status, bucket counts vs caps. Feeds AM-3."}}